People who smoke have a higher risk of losing teeth.
Anyone who smokes does not only harm the lungs, but also the teeth - this is suggested by a Potsdam long-term study.
The good news is that if you give up, the risk drops quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is shown by the long-term study of an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutritional Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers were at 2.5 to 3.6 times higher risk of losing their teeth prematurely.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth loss are caries and inflammation of the gums, stresses the DIFE.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors stress.
The relationship between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gum infections among smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
People who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short period of time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take more than ten years for the risk to return to the level of non-smokers, said lead author Thomas Dietrich of the English University of Birmingham.
Heiner Boeing, head of the study at DIFE, said: “Smoking shortens lifetimes.”
Not smoking is good for lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health until old age.
In Germany, over 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 years are affected by toothlessness, the DIFE said.
Previous studies have already indicated that smoking increases the risk of early tooth failure.
The new long-term study underpins the findings.
