Pounds rise due to accelerated wage growth in the UK
The pound jumped according to data indicating an increase in the UK's wage growth, while the FTSE 100 was boosted by the SABMiller bid target.
Between May and July, earnings without bonuses in the United Kingdom grew by 2.9% compared to the same period last year.
This percentage was the fastest and most accurate estimate of the timing of an interest rate increase since 2009.
The pound rose by more than 1% against the dollar to $1,5505 and climbed to 0.84% against the euro to €1.3730.
The FTSE 100 index closed with an increase of 1.49% to 6,229.21.
SABMiller was the outstanding share in the market and made a 20% jump after rival AB InBev’s takeover offer was received.
A transaction would combine the two largest breweries in the world and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry shares were up 0.9%, according to encouraging news from the Richemont luxury goods group.
Richemont’s latest sales figures hit all expectations and also showed sales in China – a key market for Burberry – reported growth again.
Shares of Glencore rose 5% after the mining giant said it earned $2.5 billion through a stock sale as part of its debt reduction strategy.
The stocks of the packaging and paper group Mondi were the biggest losers on the index, down 4.3% after Goldman Sachs put its rating for the company to "sell".
JD Sports rose 3.1% after the sportswear company reported a pre-tax result of 46.6 million for the half-year.
The head of JD Sports says higher wages are jeopardizing expansion.
JD Sports CEO Peter Cowgill says a higher minimum wage for UK workers could mean “more purchasing power in the pockets of potential customers.”
But it is unlikely that this purchasing power will offset the higher labor costs at his company, he says.
The cost could hit JD Sports’ expansion plans, he added, and that could mean fewer additional jobs.
