Metcash Launches Soil Consistency Campaign to Combat Aldi Incidence
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA stores from an Aldi surge in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a soil conservation campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
While Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and social media marketing, as well as events such as the Adelaide Show.
IGA dealers and suppliers jump on board, with brands like Dunsborough ice cream maker Simmo distributing samples in IGA stores and shop owners selling discounted South Australian Football League tickets to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29, when the food, alcohol and equipment wholesaler is conducting its annual investor strategy day.
Much is at stake as South Australia and Western Australia make up nearly 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the eastern states.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will snatch away about five percent of the food market in these two states, and will take away sales from all existing players, but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in revenue per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 branches in SA and 30 in WA next year, generating revenues of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and grocery store and in the amounts on Metcash’s high fixed cost basis could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash loses market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley expects Metcash’s food and grocery sales to fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, reducing market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of the Magellan Financial Group, told a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr. Douglass' comments.
But it is believed that a Metcash board member contacted Mr. Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has dropped from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenue from Metcash’s food and food trade, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, has dropped by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operating debt reduction while putting pressure on revenue and margins.
However, the wholesaler is fighting back and investing more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week, improving IGA retailers in improving their stores through fast-growing fresh foods and delivering a better selection of private label foods.
Metcash’s chief executive, Ian Morrice, says the price adjustments and store rehabilitation programs are set to go up, hoping the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis backed by Australian tennis federation president Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damages" in the recent storm surrounding his friend Nick Kyrgios and, in the opinion of the president of the Australian tennis association Steve Healy, deserves more praise than criticism for his own behavior.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, repeatedly referred to as the "Special Ks", came into the spotlight through Kyrgios' notorious confrontation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison exclaiming, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten the child."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis racket after a spasm thwarted a potential US Open win by Richard Gasquet, Healy’s Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semifinals against Britain.
“One thing I’m quite jealous of is the fact that in my opinion Thanasi was a little drawn into the dispute,” Healy said.
He broke a racket when he lost to the US Open because of a seizure, but he’s not the first player to break a racket out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know that he’s not proud of it.
But, really, he has behaved extremely well in the US open, even under the pretty provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he was treated a little too hard.
He is a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he has never had a problem with the other players, he is respected in the dressing room, he trains hard, he is in good shape, he is a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be judged on his own merit.
Healy also supported the decision to disregard Kyrgios in the important preliminary ruling, which begins on Friday, and he describes the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assured the Canberra man to return as a long-term permanent part of the team.
“First, we want the team to be fully focused on the competition and not all the controversies around [Kyrgios],” Healy said.
And I think Nick made the rise very quickly, which people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He rises in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions at the best. Some time out of the spotlight, I think it's just the best, and I think it's the best.
Europe’s refugee crisis: Hungary declares emergency, closes the border, holds back refugees
Hungary declared a state of emergency and closed the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, detaining all who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed on the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man’s land and Serbian officials reacted with outrage.
The people who had fled violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations increased.
As a police helicopter floated over them, the migrants chanted “Open the border!” and shouted insults against the Hungarian ready police.
Some rejected food and water for protest.
Serbia's foreign minister said it was "unacceptable" that migrants would be sent back from Hungary as more and more arrived from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
Talks must take place in the coming days with Brussels and other countries," Ivica Dacic said in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serb border came a day after the 28-nation bloc could not agree on a common immigration policy at a disputed meeting in Brussels.
The ministers agreed, however, to share the responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in the overwhelmed Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that the EU states would receive another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria called for a special European Union summit on Tuesday to discuss the continent's immigration crisis.
However, Hungary did not place its hopes on an early action by Brussels or its neighbours.
The state of emergency in two southern regions on Tuesday gave authorities more powers to cope with the crisis, allowing them to block roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto, meanwhile, said his country was also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after it ended a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prison inmates were used in the race to build the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a major bottleneck for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East and a point of entry into the European Union.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most of the incoming countries are economic refugees seeking a better life, not war refugees entitled to protection – a view that is strongly contrary to other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-metre (13-foot) high fence that the government had built along the southern border with Serbia a crime. These laws also establish higher prison sentences for convicted human traffickers.
"Due to the situation caused by the mass migration, the Hungarian government declares the state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: Illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament has yet to agree to the military's deployment, which is expected next week, but Associated Press reporters have seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, the country’s security adviser for Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
The authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a barbed wire train carriage had arrived to close the borders.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process the data of people and pushed a crowd to push into it.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway link between Serbia and Hungary and said they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
2016 Election: Hillary Clinton's lead over Bernie Sanders halves in national poll
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a double-digit lead in the Democratic race for nomination at the national level, but Senator Bernie Sanders is winning over her.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the primary elections (58 percent before), while Sanders is in second place, with 27 percent (up 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether to run for president, receives support from 15 percent of the Democratic constituents of the primary elections.
More than five months before the presidential elections begin, most Democratic voters say it’s too early to say their opinions are firm on which candidates they will support.
But Clinton’s supporters are more consistent in their election than those of the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups, while Sanders made some profits.
Clinton holds a big lead in women and moderates, but those protrusions have decreased.
Their support for the men has dropped significantly, and Sanders is only 5 points behind.
Clinton’s advantage among Democratic voters under 50 has faded, and she and Sanders are now on par.
But Clinton still has a big lead among the older voters.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a two-point lead in the Liberals, but Sanders now has a five-point lead in that group.
Approximately half of the Democratic constituents in the primary elections nationwide say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if she were nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations and another 15 percent would support her only because she is the candidate.
6 percent wouldn’t support it.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton’s current supporters are especially enthusiastic about her.
The views are more mixed among those who do not currently support Clinton - only about a quarter would enthusiastically support them.
While 48 percent of Democratic primary voters say they support Clinton with enthusiasm, fewer Republican voters say this about their top candidate Donald Trump (35 percent).
When Clinton’s supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16 percent), followed by the belief that it’s time for a woman to become president (13 percent) and that she is the best candidate for the job (10 percent).
Clinton’s supporters also mention their connection to Bill Clinton (9%).
Consent to deal with the problems and the selectability are also cited.
As the vice president throws potential for the presidential office into the scales, 57 percent of Democratic primary voters want to see him in the race — though a third believes he shouldn’t.
When Democratic primary voters are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the top.
More than half of Clinton’s supporters say Biden would be their second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democrats, Hillary Clinton’s lead to Sanders increases, from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as the candidate with the best chances of winning the election; however, that figure has dropped by 78 percent last month.
Biden is by far a second on this measurement, but the percentage that considers him to be the "most selectable" has increased.
Nevertheless, when asked what is more important to a candidate, Democratic voters raise questions about electability.
Similar to last month, no single Democratic candidate or potential candidate stands out as unacceptable for these primary voters.
Democratic candidates or potential candidates perform well on some important traits among electors of their party’s primary elections.
Majorities consider Clinton, Sanders and Biden to be honest and trustworthy and equipped with strong leadership skills.
Biden scores best on honesty among the three candidates, while Clinton’s strength is the lead.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters don’t believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say that about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent don’t think so.
Democratic primary voters generally also see Clinton, Sanders, and Biden ideologically in line with their views.
In all these measurements, about a quarter of democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
As questions about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and a server continue to be asked during her tenure as foreign minister, most Democratic voters in the primary elections are satisfied with her explanation of the matter and say that it has not overall influenced her opinions.
But it’s a different story in the American public as a whole.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third is satisfied.
Public opinion on this matter was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no impact on their general opinions of Clinton, although 36 percent said their opinion of her had worsened.
It’s mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views of Clinton have gotten worse.
Although Clinton is considered honest and trustworthy by her party’s voters, this continues to be a problem for them among registered voters overall: only 32 percent see them as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month and 15 points less since May.
62% of voters do not consider them an honest and trustworthy person.
At the same time, 55 percent of voters across the country also view Trump as unhonest and untrustworthy.
However, Clinton and Trump get good scores in leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson and Bush scored best with honesty.
A majority consider Sanders more honest, but like Carson, many have no opinion of him.
The error rate for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the primary elections is 6 percentage points.
