Five Brotherhood Members Burdened with Death of Baruch College Newcomer
Almost two years after a student died during an abusive ritual of a student connection in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges are filed against five people.
Members of New York's Baruch College Pi-Delta-Psi Brotherhood brutally attacked Chun "Michael" Deng during an introductory ritual in September 2013, delaying his transport to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he was blindfolded with a 30-pound backpack full of sand, and repeatedly attacked while trying to reach a target over a frozen field.
Mr. Deng finally complained about a headache, then he fell unconscious.
The members of the Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call 911 after Deng passed out and were supposedly waiting an hour before taking him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had time to change Deng’s clothes, google his symptoms and contact Andy Meng, the national president of the Brotherhood, for advice, Police Chief Chris Wagner said at a press conference.
"At this point, the members began to hide utensils and put the welfare of the brotherhood above that of Michael Deng," Wagner said.
He could not be revived, and he died the next morning from his injuries.
According to an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly injured with blunt force on the head, hull and thigh.
"Too many families have been destroyed by the harassment of the Brotherhood, and at least one student has died of harassment every year since 1970," Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng's family, said in a statement.
Brotherhoods and their members must be held accountable, and this step by authorities is very important.
A County Grand Jury of Monroe recommended a third-degree murder charge for the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the Brotherhood, including Mr. Meng, are also charged with harassing attacks and the formation of a criminal association.
"We don't just want to hold the people involved accountable, but if there is an organization that has sanctioned this - officially or unofficially - we will also hold them accountable," Wagner said at a press conference on Tuesday.
Baruch College has banned the Brotherhood, and the National Brotherhood has revoked its membership in the local group.
This will happen when the Fed raises interest rates.
An interest rate hike is coming, and the hikes will falter, yields on bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into a recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long this will last and how long it will last.
In particular, history offers little guidance for the economy.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
Therefore, representatives of the U.S. central bank have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when it begins to raise interest rates, but rather on the period required for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that all the excitement may have been exaggerated due to an interest rate hike.
“The first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of ‘cheap money’,” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement to customers.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal heights, but still to low levels to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here is a historically trend-based look at how some sectors of the economy might react:
As the market has seen last month, anticipating interest rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
As soon as the increase arrives, the influence is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency for asset income to be squeezed 12 to 24 months after the first increase, perhaps reflecting again the delay in monetary policy,” German bank analysts said in a recent study of what happens after the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
More specifically, the market has been mostly on the upward trend over the past 35 years - about 14 percent - on the way to interest rate hike, fairly flat in the 250 days afterwards (average profit of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return of 14.4 percent in the past six cycles, according to a recent analysis released by the Asge set at the Bob Doll, Chief Investment Board.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on the stocks tends to occur later in the upward cycle and the return is beginning to decrease.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate increases often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
Most notably, gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point when the Fed raises interest rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 interest rate increases since 1950 were only twice the nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes in such a fragile economic environment could be risky and raise the question “whether it’s different this time around,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have set their sights on a Fed interest rate hike throughout the year, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week ending Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading indicates only a 25 percent probability.
“In our study, all of the increase cycles from 1950 to today took place in a super cycle with increasing momentum in GDP, shading pre-recession heights very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
In contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and that’s 74 months so far.
The fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate increase, and the pattern is pretty similar to that in the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic price.
For bonds, yields seem to change direction as soon as the first increase/reduction occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields drop immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab’s strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will cause yields between longer and shorter bonds to shrink closer and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-yield bonds often bring better returns in such a climate, although “we’re still cautious to expect higher returns,” Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones says that markets have already adjusted to Fed strategy expectations.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some indications that the market has adapted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy," she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit margins have expanded, and volatility has increased – all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
On the whole, companies that do the bulk of their business in the U.S. will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debts will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market and so does financing their debts.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks tend to react extremely positively three months after an initial interest rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Strong-balance sheet companies averaged 5 percentage points higher than weak-balance sheet companies after each of the 1994, 1999 and 2004 interest rate increases.
Companies with high returns on capital and low volatility in their shares also surpassed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points).
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see profits from higher yields, even if experts disagree on how quickly this will happen.
