At their most anticipated meeting this year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduran Mahagoni table to decide whether it’s time to raise the lead rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Threatening above them at one end of the ornate, two-story meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation’s economic interests first.
The central bank has a double mandate from Congress: to maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the great recession, the Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict, and it will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to start off from the unprecedented incentive of the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Although most of the economy’s data shows it is growing solidly, recent turmoil in global financial markets could make already cautious Fed representatives anxious to increase this volatility by raising interest rates on federal bonds – even if it is only a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the most important thing they observe,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to continue to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed is going to do, which in itself is unsettling the financial market.
About half of economists surveyed recently by Bloomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
The financial markets, however, expect a wait for the Fed, with a key indicator indicating only a 30% chance of an increase.
This indicates a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate, unless strategists mitigate the blow by promising that another increase is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped 228.89 points or 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The action was triggered by expectations that the Fed policy would maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed would lift the rates at this point,” he said.
If she does, “they would have to go very far in their statement to calm the financial markets so that they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of recovery in the US.
Yellen had said in spring and early summer that despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress was needed, she expected a rate increase this year.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labor market this year was solid.
The unemployment rate dropped to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed sees as full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And while inflation was constantly below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, Fed officials said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher interest rates and needs them because of the tension in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world shrank at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell more than 16% below its peak in May when investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below the May high.
For Fed representatives, market turmoil influences the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the past few weeks had not occurred, they would be putting the reins on in this session,” said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the U.S. Federal Reserve.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there are almost no reliable data describing developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not one of the main concerns of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed monetary authority has become the world.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere indication by then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “constrict” its monetary expansion sparked confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Her decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global asset management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, noted this month that “the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that seem to be unrelated to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, which advocates an interest rate increase, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia prompted the Fed to cut its lead interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions “despite limited noticeable impact on U.S. growth,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed officials reversed these cuts.
The Fed should put aspects of financial stability first only during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market collapse, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
The recent turmoil does not come close to this level, he said.
"She certainly doesn't want to get into the situation where she's afraid of a rate hike because markets are upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don’t think it should be ahead of time.
