Four-fold increase in children’s intake of hand disinfectants in the last 4 years
Toxic control centers in the U.S. report a nearly 400 percent increase in the number of children under the age of twelve who swallow heavily alcoholic hand disinfectants, according to the Georgia Poison Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Center, cases of hand disinfectant revenues among children under 12 years of age reported by poison control centers increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children are coming to these products more and more frequently, and unfortunately, a percentage of them end up going to the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children drink disinfectants intentionally, while some do so to impress their friends or because of a trial of courage on social media.
Videos on YouTube show how teenagers drink disinfectants only because of a cheap experience.
Teenagers reportedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to get a harder drink.
Younger children can be attracted by attractive scents of disinfectants.
“A child doesn’t think this is bad for him,” Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand disinfectants) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with strawberry, grape and orange scent, which are very appealing for children.
Hand disinfectants contain somewhere between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few splashes can lead to alcohol poisoning.
“It’s highly concentrated alcohol,” said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison emergency call center at the University of Kansas hospital, Fox 4 station in Kansa City.
So, you wouldn’t let a sip of whiskey stand around, but people leave these hand disinfectants within reach of children, and if children get to it, then it’s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four shots of strawberry-smelling hand sanitizer at school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol concentration was 179, twice the threshold legally considered drunk in an adult, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside of Atlanta.
Nhaijah laughed her words and was unable to leave when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors watched her overnight in a separate children's hospital for signs of brain trauma as the girl fell through the alcohol and hit her head, Ritchey said.
"That was very frightening," said Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, CNN.
It could have been deadly for my child.
Lopez has recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic products or disinfectant wipes and store hand disinfectants out of the child’s reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants were associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand disinfectants containing a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect that the product contained methanol, a deadly solution, rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as an active ingredient.
