Robotic cars: Government wants to lead Germany
According to the will of the Federal Government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the transformation of the car.
The Federal Cabinet decided on Wednesday a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which includes investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the sidelines of the IAA car show of a "new age of mobility".
Automated and connected driving will increase traffic safety and reduce traffic congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his colleagues from the G7 countries, who also meet with representatives of industry at the IAA.
The strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport stresses the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid transition to digital radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being built on the Highway 9 in Bavaria.
In order to ensure that the driver "does not have to be burdened with additional liability risks", the federal government wants to "review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt to the new developments".
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to raise the maximum permissible speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres per hour.
The Federal Government also wants to push for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
In automated driving, the car increasingly takes the lead, the driver becomes more and more a passenger.
The technology is mainly based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study submitted by the Ministry of Economic Affairs, highly automated driving on highways will be technically possible by 2020.
However, driverless vehicles are to be expected on public roads "only far after 2020".
The value added in the field of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the German site is estimated by the authors of the study by 2025 at around 8.4 billion euros.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to greater safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD traffic policymaker Sören Bartol.
However, the issue of liability for accidents and the security of drivers' personal data must be clearly clarified.
However, German self-driving cars still look skeptical - much more so than French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the testing organisation Dekra, published on Wednesday, concluded that only 8% of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32% expect it in 20 years, 31% do not believe it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars to be used by 2025, while in the United States 33 percent.
In any case, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital federation Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to surrender control throughout the entire journey on all roads.
On the highway, 15 percent of traffic flows, 45 percent in traffic jams.
Almost one in four would not leave the car in control under any circumstances.
