Xi urges to open the economy to the world more broadly
The economy needs to open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday to a group tasked with steering the reform.
“China should work to attract foreign investment and expertise and improve strategies for business start-ups,” he said in a speech at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group for Deepening a Comprehensive Reform.
Promoting new startups and driving reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership group has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list on regulating market access, relaxing border control policies, encouraging state enterprises (SOEs), acquiring private capital, and overhaul of the resident reporting system.
According to the statement, a negative list is created that identifies sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually tested and improved by test programs.
The initiative is important as it assigns a greater role to the market in the allocation of resources, ensures a legal business environment and makes the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls over the powers given to companies and ensure that companies decide how to conduct their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of an offer to open up government-controlled sectors, further areas will be opened up for private investment.
"The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide better services for them," the statement said.
In addition, it will make it easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the "green card" by optimizing the requirements and facilitating the application process.
