EU to double mercury limit in predatory fish
The European Commission intends to double the limits for mercury in large predatory fishes and thus suggest a significantly higher dose of nerve poison for consumers.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, sharply criticized the plans: "The risks and side effects of misguided industrial and environmental policies are being passed on to pregnant women and young children with full force," said Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of nerve toxins for large fish at the end of the food chain such as shark or swordfish are to be raised from one milligram of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily contaminated with mercury that, on the basis of the limits still in force, about 50 percent of the catches cannot be sold.
After doubling the limits, only 14.5 percent would be unavailable.
In return for this easing, according to Foodwatch, the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
But Foodwatch called this a "trick" because smaller peace fish, such as carp, are usually loaded so low that they already meet the planned maximum levels today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious distraction maneuver, which alone helps the economy," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a heavy metal that is highly toxic to humans and is heavily enriched through the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The Federal Government warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn children".
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment declares on its homepage in view of the current maximum values that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through coal combustion.
German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tons of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written report from the Federal Ministry of the Environment to the Greens parliamentarian Annalena Baerbock.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, has been "permanently and extensively exceeded", the "mirror" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, European-wide warnings about mercury in fish were already among the most common health risks reported in the EU’s RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.mercury-action.foodwatch.de
